[5] Taiwan
Date: 8 Nov 2006
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: Taiwan Headlines - Taipei Taiwan [edited]
<http://english.www.gov.tw/TaiwanHeadlines/index.jsp?categid=10&recordid=101489>

The head of the Department of Health apologized on Monday [6 Nov 2006] for
a statement made by a Center for Disease Control official, who allegedly
said that "dengue fever is an unbreakable curse on the people of Kaohsiung."
Disavowing the statement, Hou Sheng-mao also pledged to step up his
agency's fight against the outbreak of the disease, which has infected 575
people since the beginning of the summer and resulted in 2 deaths from
among the 14 who contracted dengue hemorrhagic fever.
Most of the cases have been concentrated in southern Taiwan, with 404
patients in Kaohsiung City, 156 in Kaohsiung County, 9 in Pingdong County,
2 in Tainan County, 2 in Tainan City, one in Taipei County, and one in
Keelung City.
The DOH has come under some pressure this year [2006] because the outbreak
has exceeded the maximum targets set at the beginning of October 2006 of
"under 500 dengue fever cases and zero deaths from the disease."
Hou said that unless the outbreak is out of control, the central government
had no plans to take over, but he indicated the DOH was already pooling the
resources of local and central governments, including the Environmental
Protection Administration and Defense Ministry, to assist in disinfecting
and spraying pesticides in affected areas.
CDC Deputy Director and spokesman Chou Chih-hao said that incentives to
report dengue fever cases will be in place from now to the end of the year
as part of an effort to fight the disease. He said that an outpatient
doctor who reports a dengue fever case will be rewarded TWD 1000 [USD 31],
while an inpatient doctor be awarded TWD 3000 [USD 92] for every case reported.
--
