[7] Cuba
Date: 15 Nov 2006
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: Houston Chronicle - United States [edited]
<http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/health/4335279.html>

An epidemic of dengue fever that flooded hospitals and may have killed as
many as 100 Cubans has been brought under control by a fumigation campaign.
The outbreak was the worst in a quarter of a century and appears to have
afflicted thousands during its peak in September and October 2006.
Infections have slowed to a few dozen new cases this month [November 2006],
said a senior doctor familiar with the scope of the epidemic, who added
that the response was initially slowed by government secrecy.
Cuba's Public Health Ministry subsequently confirmed the outbreak.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Although the Cuban government has acknowledged this significant dengue
epidemic and reported it to the Panamerican Health Organization, the
numbers of cases of dengue and DHF and their locations have not been released.
